WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.360
So, I want you to picture this.

2
00:00:03.360 --> 00:00:04.960
You've studied for weeks.

3
00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:05.720
Oh yeah.

4
00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:07.440
You know the material backward and forward,

5
00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:09.920
you completely nailed the practice test, right?

6
00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:12.920
But the second you sit down in that quiet room,

7
00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:14.720
the fluorescent lights are buzzing,

8
00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:16.480
you flip the exam paper over,

9
00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:17.880
and you just completely freeze.

10
00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:19.880
Like your mind goes entirely blank.

11
00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:21.760
Completely blank, why does that happen?

12
00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:23.760
Well, if you ask a psychologist,

13
00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:25.000
they're gonna tell you one thing.

14
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:26.880
But if you ask a neurobiologist,

15
00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:28.960
they will give you a completely different answer.

16
00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:31.160
And, you know, the neither of them is wrong.

17
00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:31.960
Right.

18
00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:34.240
So today, we're doing a deep dive

19
00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:35.960
into the dynamic relationship

20
00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:38.880
between neuroscience and psychology.

21
00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:40.920
We're unpacking how these two fields

22
00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:42.920
don't actually compete.

23
00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:45.160
Our mission today is to show how they come together

24
00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:49.040
to fully explain like the entire human experience.

25
00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:50.440
Yeah, because freezing up on a test

26
00:00:50.440 --> 00:00:53.480
is this universally frustrating human experience.

27
00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:54.840
And it perfectly illustrates

28
00:00:54.840 --> 00:00:57.080
this massive misconception that people have.

29
00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:58.000
Okay, let's unpack this.

30
00:00:58.000 --> 00:00:58.920
What misconception?

31
00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:02.760
Well, people tend to think that psychology

32
00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:07.640
and neuroscience are sort of fighting

33
00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:10.360
to be the right way to view human behavior.

34
00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:11.920
Like it has to be one or the other.

35
00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:12.760
But they're not.

36
00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:13.800
No, not at all.

37
00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:16.280
They're actually looking at the exact same event

38
00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:17.840
and the exact same student.

39
00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:20.240
But they're just asking fundamentally different questions

40
00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:21.880
to gather entirely different data.

41
00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:23.920
Right, because to the untrained eye,

42
00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:25.720
a freeze is just a freeze.

43
00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:27.160
But if we view this behavior

44
00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:29.080
through the psychological lens,

45
00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:32.040
we are really looking at meaning and context.

46
00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:35.040
Exactly, the psychology lens focuses on the mind.

47
00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:38.240
Right, a psychologist is looking at that student at the desk

48
00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:42.560
and asking about their internal and external reality.

49
00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:44.680
Like what did that person perceive in that moment?

50
00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:46.520
What did they expect was gonna happen?

51
00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:48.080
Yeah, they're examining the thoughts,

52
00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:50.760
the emotions, maybe the ingrained habits

53
00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:52.440
that shape that freezing behavior.

54
00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:54.400
Like is there some deep-seated fear or failure?

55
00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:58.040
Or maybe the specific phrasing of that very first question

56
00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:01.400
triggered a memory of a past academic disaster or something?

57
00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:02.680
Precisely.

58
00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:05.400
The psychological lens is deeply concerned

59
00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:07.440
with the subjective experience.

60
00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:09.840
It's looking at the threat appraisal happening

61
00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:10.920
in that student's mind.

62
00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:12.480
But then you swap lenses, right?

63
00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:14.240
You look through the neuroscience lens

64
00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:17.480
and the focus shifts entirely to the physical mechanisms

65
00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:20.440
like operating inside the actual nervous system.

66
00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:21.880
Yeah, the physical hardware.

67
00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:22.720
Yeah.

68
00:02:22.760 --> 00:02:25.160
The scientists isn't asking about the student's fear

69
00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:28.680
of failure or their past trauma.

70
00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:30.800
They don't care about the bad test and third grade.

71
00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:35.160
Right, they are asking which specific brain circuits,

72
00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:39.320
which stress hormones, which autonomic responses were firing,

73
00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:41.600
what exact neurotransmitters were active,

74
00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:44.600
the literal millisecond that student froze.

75
00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:47.240
And what's fascinating here is that this is where that

76
00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:49.120
misconception usually crops up, right?

77
00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:51.080
People often think, well, one of these explanations

78
00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:52.560
has to be the real root cause.

79
00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:55.320
Yes, but neither level replaces the other.

80
00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:57.600
That is so critical to understand.

81
00:02:57.600 --> 00:02:59.760
Psychology describes the mind and behavior.

82
00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:01.120
It's what a person does,

83
00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:03.320
what they feel, think, learn and report.

84
00:03:03.320 --> 00:03:05.080
While neuroscience is just explaining

85
00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:07.520
the biological implementation of those things.

86
00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:08.680
Exactly.

87
00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:11.280
Both explanations for our frozen student

88
00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:14.400
are 100% true at the exact same time.

89
00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:16.360
Okay, let me try an analogy here.

90
00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:18.280
I like to think of this like a computer.

91
00:03:18.280 --> 00:03:19.920
Okay, I like what this is going.

92
00:03:19.920 --> 00:03:22.640
So psychology is sort of like analyzing

93
00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:25.480
a software program's user interface, right?

94
00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:26.920
You're looking at the menus, the butters,

95
00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:29.520
what the user actually experiences on the screen.

96
00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:31.040
Yeah, output in the interaction, yeah.

97
00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:34.280
But neuroscience is like opening up the computer case

98
00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:35.280
and looking at the hardware.

99
00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:38.240
You're measuring the electrical currents on the motherboard,

100
00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.040
the physical memory chips, the fan speed.

101
00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:42.560
That is a perfect way to look at it.

102
00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:44.000
You have a software experience

103
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:45.560
and the physical hardware mechanism.

104
00:03:45.560 --> 00:03:48.400
Oh, wait, let me push back on that for a second.

105
00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:52.400
Because if our neuroscience tools get so incredibly advanced

106
00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:54.840
that we can eventually map out the physical hardware

107
00:03:54.840 --> 00:03:57.480
perfectly, like down the every single

108
00:03:57.480 --> 00:03:59.120
atom and electrical current,

109
00:03:59.120 --> 00:04:02.080
do we even need to study the software anymore?

110
00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:02.920
Right.

111
00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:05.440
If we know the hardware, why bother with the psychology?

112
00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:07.440
Yeah, why talk about abstract feelings

113
00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.680
if I can just mathematically measure your exact dopamine

114
00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:11.960
and cortisol levels?

115
00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.840
It's a really common debate.

116
00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:15.960
But abandoning the psychological context

117
00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:17.360
is a total dead end.

118
00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:18.080
Why?

119
00:04:18.080 --> 00:04:19.760
Because knowing the physical hardware

120
00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:22.240
doesn't tell you anything about the intent of the system.

121
00:04:22.240 --> 00:04:23.080
Yeah.

122
00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:26.360
Even if you map every single electrical impulse,

123
00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:29.520
each lens is answering a completely different kind of question.

124
00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:30.360
Oh, I see.

125
00:04:30.360 --> 00:04:32.160
You absolutely need the psychological context

126
00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:36.240
to understand why that biological mechanism matters

127
00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:38.440
in the real world, like what actually triggered

128
00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:40.200
those electrical currents in the first place?

129
00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:43.920
So to really grasp how deeply these lenses rely on each other,

130
00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:46.280
we have to look at the scale of human behavior.

131
00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:49.080
Because a single action like our student freezing

132
00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:51.160
is actually the result of processes happening

133
00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:52.560
across a mass spectrum.

134
00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:54.000
Right, the levels of analysis.

135
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:54.840
Exactly.

136
00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:56.840
At the very foundation, you have this microscopic level.

137
00:04:56.840 --> 00:04:58.120
We're talking molecules.

138
00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:00.520
This is where neurotransmitters and hormones operate.

139
00:05:00.520 --> 00:05:03.520
And then as you zoom out, you hit the cellular level.

140
00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:06.120
So now you're looking at networks of individual neurons

141
00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:07.240
or glia cells.

142
00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:08.800
Right, zoom out again.

143
00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:10.800
And you're looking at entire brain circuits

144
00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:12.400
communicating with each other.

145
00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:15.080
Further still, you're observing the whole brain.

146
00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:17.440
And then the individual's outward behavior, right?

147
00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:17.760
Yes.

148
00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:20.520
And eventually, you zoom all the way out

149
00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:23.360
to see how that specific behavior interacts

150
00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:25.880
with an impact broader society.

151
00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:26.680
Wow.

152
00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:29.040
So if you look at the diagram on this slide

153
00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:30.520
from our source nodes, visually, you

154
00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:33.160
can see how researchers try to map this out.

155
00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:35.440
They try to link the brain activity

156
00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:38.440
at those lower levels to the complex behaviors

157
00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:39.440
at the higher levels.

158
00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:41.680
It is a massive puzzle of causality.

159
00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:43.680
Yeah, and visually mapping the link

160
00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:46.320
between the brain and behavior is wild.

161
00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:48.080
If you look at model A in the nodes,

162
00:05:48.080 --> 00:05:51.200
it shows that a subset of neural activity patterns

163
00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:54.680
in our brain is linked to all natural behaviors.

164
00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:55.280
That makes sense.

165
00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:55.760
It does.

166
00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:56.920
It's the baseline assumption.

167
00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:58.760
But then you look at models B and C.

168
00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:01.280
And visually, you can see that sometimes

169
00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:04.000
a really small subset of activity patterns

170
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.680
links to a specific small subset of behaviors.

171
00:06:06.680 --> 00:06:07.040
Right.

172
00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:09.480
But crucially, not all brain activity

173
00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:11.840
results in a behavioral output.

174
00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:12.680
Wait, really?

175
00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:14.240
So my brain is doing things that don't

176
00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:15.720
results in any action.

177
00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:16.920
Oh, constantly.

178
00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:18.840
Your brain is doing an enormous amount

179
00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:21.840
of background processing that never translates

180
00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:23.400
into any behavior at all.

181
00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:25.200
It's like going back to your analogy,

182
00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:27.240
a computer running a huge background update

183
00:06:27.240 --> 00:06:29.320
while you're just reading a web page.

184
00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:31.360
The neural activity is furious,

185
00:06:31.360 --> 00:06:33.240
but your hands aren't moving any differently.

186
00:06:33.240 --> 00:06:35.320
That is so wild to think about.

187
00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:38.760
But then visually, models D and E show something

188
00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:40.360
even more confusing.

189
00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:41.960
It's the many to one problem.

190
00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:45.520
You can have multiple completely different neural patterns

191
00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:47.920
underlying just one single behavior.

192
00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:48.560
Yes.

193
00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:50.520
The exact same physical movement

194
00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:53.080
can be driven by entirely different circuits.

195
00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:53.400
Right.

196
00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:55.200
Like throwing your hands up in the air.

197
00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:56.360
You could be doing that because you're

198
00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:58.040
cheering for your favorite team.

199
00:06:58.040 --> 00:06:59.920
Or you could be defensively bracing

200
00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:02.200
because something is falling on you.

201
00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:04.520
To the naked eye, the behavior is identical.

202
00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:06.360
But the neural patterns are totally different.

203
00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:08.720
And you know, the brain does the exact reverse, too.

204
00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:09.840
No one did any problem.

205
00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:10.840
Exactly.

206
00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:12.760
One single neural firing pattern

207
00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:15.840
might be involved in multiple wildly different behaviors.

208
00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:19.120
Like a specific circuit involving the amygdala

209
00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:21.840
might be recruited when you are terrified of a snake.

210
00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:24.040
But that same underlying circuitry

211
00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:26.080
might also be heavily engaged

212
00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:27.920
when you were intensely excited,

213
00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:29.680
like riding a massive roller coaster.

214
00:07:29.680 --> 00:07:30.520
Oh, wow.

215
00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:33.240
So the context completely changes the output.

216
00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:35.280
But that raises a huge question.

217
00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:38.480
If one behavior can have multiple different neural patterns

218
00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:40.720
behind it and one neural pattern

219
00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:45.400
can drive multiple behaviors, how do researchers ever figure

220
00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:47.360
out what's causing what?

221
00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:49.760
Honestly, that is the defining struggle

222
00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:52.920
of the entire field, untangling that web

223
00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:55.080
requires highly sophisticated data gathering

224
00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:58.520
from both the psychological side and the neurobiological side.

225
00:07:58.520 --> 00:08:00.680
And we really have to understand

226
00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:02.160
Let's break down that data gathering.

227
00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:03.120
Because I think we need to clear up

228
00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:05.160
how empirical psychology actually is.

229
00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:06.920
Psychology doesn't just talk about feelings.

230
00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:09.640
It turns the messy, subjective human experience

231
00:08:09.640 --> 00:08:11.920
into hard, quantifiable data.

232
00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:12.880
Oh, absolutely.

233
00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:14.920
They aren't just observing behavior and guessing.

234
00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:17.000
They are putting actual numbers to it.

235
00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:17.720
Right.

236
00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:19.400
Through highly controlled tasks,

237
00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:22.880
psychologists measure reaction times down to the millisecond.

238
00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:26.360
They track accuracy rates, analyze specific choices,

239
00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:30.040
and map out the exact errors someone makes under pressure.

240
00:08:30.040 --> 00:08:33.520
And they also use very validated self-reporting structures.

241
00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:36.160
Patients systematically categorize their thoughts,

242
00:08:36.160 --> 00:08:38.040
their symptoms, their beliefs.

243
00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:41.200
It's a rigorous quantification of the mind.

244
00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:43.280
Meanwhile, neuroscience is trying

245
00:08:43.280 --> 00:08:45.880
to turn the physical nervous system into data, right?

246
00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:46.680
Yes.

247
00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:48.760
They use functional measurements, advanced imaging,

248
00:08:48.760 --> 00:08:50.800
animal research, and pharmacology.

249
00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:52.640
But every single one of those neuroscience

250
00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:55.040
cools comes with a heavy trade-off, doesn't it?

251
00:08:55.040 --> 00:08:57.080
It really is a constant balancing act.

252
00:08:57.080 --> 00:09:00.320
Researchers basically have to navigate four main constraints.

253
00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:02.480
You have spatial detail, which is where it happens.

254
00:09:02.480 --> 00:09:02.980
OK.

255
00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:05.400
Timing, which is when it happens, invasiveness,

256
00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:08.040
how much you have to disrupt the body and causal power.

257
00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:10.000
Causal power just meaning proving

258
00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.280
that manipulating circuit x directly causes behavior y.

259
00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:13.840
Exactly.

260
00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:15.680
Proving true cause and effect.

261
00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:18.920
So take functional MRI, or FMRI, for example.

262
00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:21.040
It provides breathtaking spatial detail.

263
00:09:21.040 --> 00:09:24.080
You can see exactly where activity is happening deep inside

264
00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:25.400
the brain down to the millimeter.

265
00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:27.600
But its timing is inherently flawed, right?

266
00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:28.440
Yes.

267
00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:31.640
Because FMRI doesn't measure electricity directly,

268
00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:32.920
it measures blood flow.

269
00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:33.120
Right.

270
00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:35.560
The blood oxygen level of dependent signal.

271
00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:37.480
And blood takes a few seconds

272
00:09:37.480 --> 00:09:39.200
to rush into an active brain region.

273
00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:40.120
Exactly.

274
00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:43.160
Neurofiring happens in milliseconds.

275
00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:45.120
But the blood flow takes seconds.

276
00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:48.040
So by the time the FMRI registers the activity,

277
00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:50.760
the actual thought or impulse is already passed.

278
00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:54.400
It's like seeing the smoke, but missing the actual explosion.

279
00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:56.720
You know where it happened, but you completely

280
00:09:56.720 --> 00:10:00.000
missed the exact millisecond the spark ignited.

281
00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:00.840
That's a great way to put it.

282
00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:03.000
Now if you want that millisecond precision,

283
00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.040
you use something like an EEG, measuring

284
00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:06.640
the electrical signals right on the scalp.

285
00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:08.200
But then you lose the spatial detail, right?

286
00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:08.880
Yes.

287
00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:10.520
You know exactly when it happened.

288
00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:12.800
But you can't tell exactly where deep inside the brain

289
00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:14.720
tissue, the signal originated from.

290
00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:17.200
And then there's the hurdle of causal power.

291
00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:18.920
Because if you want high causal power,

292
00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:20.200
