00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:50.640
OK, visually the animation is showing

308
00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:52.600
these glowing network fibers firing

309
00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:55.000
and rapid succession across totally different regions

310
00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:56.800
of the brain, like all simultaneously.

311
00:10:56.800 --> 00:10:57.760
It's mesmerizing.

312
00:10:57.760 --> 00:10:58.640
It really is.

313
00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:00.640
What strikes you is the sheer speed

314
00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:02.480
and the interconnectedness of it all.

315
00:11:02.480 --> 00:11:05.360
It visually proves that the brain is this continuous,

316
00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:07.040
wildly dynamic web.

317
00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:09.000
Yeah, completely shatters that old myth

318
00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.320
that the brain works in isolated buckets.

319
00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:13.560
Right, like the idea that vision happens

320
00:11:13.560 --> 00:11:15.960
in one quiet little corner and emotion

321
00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:19.560
happens in a completely separate, disconnected room.

322
00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:20.680
That's just not true.

323
00:11:20.680 --> 00:11:21.680
Not at all.

324
00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:25.200
It is a relentless rapid fire symphony.

325
00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:28.200
Everything is talking to everything else all the time.

326
00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:31.760
And building on that dynamic GIF we just saw,

327
00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:33.760
we really have to factor in neural variability.

